# Dev-Timr Configuration
# Copy this file to .env and configure your settings

# ==============================================================================
# SUPABASE CONFIGURATION
# ==============================================================================
# Your Supabase project URL
# Get this from: https://app.supabase.com/project/_/settings/api
SUPABASE_URL=https://your-project-id.supabase.co

# Your Supabase Anon/Public Key
# Note: Anon keys are designed to be public-facing. Security is enforced via
# Row Level Security (RLS) policies on your database tables.
# Get this from: https://app.supabase.com/project/_/settings/api
SUPABASE_ANON_KEY=your-anon-key-here

# ==============================================================================
# GITHUB OAUTH CONFIGURATION
# ==============================================================================
# GitHub OAuth App Client ID
# Create an OAuth app at: https://github.com/settings/developers
# Set Authorization callback URL to: http://localhost (for device flow)
GITHUB_CLIENT_ID=your-github-client-id-here

# ==============================================================================
# NOTES FOR SELF-HOSTED DEPLOYMENTS
# ==============================================================================
# If you're running your own instance:
# 1. Create a Supabase project at https://supabase.com
# 2. Run the database migrations from /supabase/migrations/ (if available)
# 3. Deploy the Edge Function from /supabase/functions/github-login/
# 4. Set JWT_SECRET in your Supabase Edge Function secrets
# 5. Create a GitHub OAuth app for authentication
# 6. Configure Row Level Security policies (see SECURITY.md)
# 7. Copy this file to .env and fill in your values

# ==============================================================================
# FOR CONTRIBUTORS USING THE DEFAULT SHARED INSTANCE
# ==============================================================================
# If you're contributing and want to use the shared instance for testing:
# 1. Don't create a .env file - the app will use defaults
# 2. The shared instance has RLS policies to protect user data
# 3. Each user's data is isolated by their GitHub authentication
# 4. For production use, we recommend running your own instance
